      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "tone": "info",
          "title": "Also",
          "body": "1 teaspoon bicarbonate soda."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Method"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Grease a fairly deep 1.2 Litre baking dish with butter.  Place the dates in a heatproof bowl with the bicarbonate of soda and stir.  Pour over the boiling water, cover the bowl with cling film and leave the dates to soak for around 30 minutes before mashing the dates with a fork to a pulp.  Set aside while you make the sponge.  Preheat the oven to 180C/160 Fan/350F/Gas mark 4."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Using an electric mixer or wooden spoon, cream the soft butter and sugar together for about 5 minutes or until very light and fluffy.  Beat in the eggs, a little at a time, waiting until they are fully incorporated before adding the rest. Beat in the vanilla extract, treacle and golden syrup."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Fold in half the flour, folding lightly until no streaks of flour can be seen.  Fold in half the milk, then repeat with the remaining flour and milk.  Stir the mashed dates and any remaining liquid into the batter until smooth.  The batter will look like a curdled mess at this point, but don’t worry."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Pour the batter into the greased tin and bake for 40-50 minutes or until the pudding has risen, is springy to the touch and a skewer inserted in the middle of the cake emerges with no raw batter clinging to it.  A little stickiness is fine!"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "While the sponge is baking, make the sauce.  Melt the sugar, butter and treacle in a large saucepan over a low heat. Once the butter has melted and the sugar has dissolved, stir in the cream.  Turn the heat up slightly and when the sauce is bubbling remove from the heat.  Cover to keep warm."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "As soon as the pudding is out of the oven, skewer it all over with a cocktail stick or cake tester and pour over about half of the sauce, allowing it to soak into the sponge.  Using a spatula, spread the sauce to the edges so the entire sponge is covered in the sauce."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Leave the pudding to stand for about 30 minutes before serving with ice cream, double cream or custard, and the remaining toffee sauce."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "heading": "If something goes wrong",
          "intro": "A few of the more common issues, and what tends to fix them.",
          "items": [
            {
              "symptom": "Mixture won't set",
              "cause": "Sugar didn't reach the right stage, or temperature was guessed.",
              "fix": "Use a sugar thermometer. Stages: soft-ball 115°C, hard-ball 125°C, soft-crack 135°C, hard-crack 150°C. Cold-water tests work but the thermometer doesn't lie."
            },
            {
              "symptom": "Sugar crystallised",
              "cause": "Mixture stirred after it started bubbling, or a stray crystal landed on the side of the pan.",
              "fix": "Don't stir once the sugar is dissolved. Brush the inside of the pan with a wet pastry brush to wash crystals down."
            },
            {
              "symptom": "Fudge is grainy",
              "cause": "Beaten too soon — while still too hot.",
              "fix": "Cool to 43°C before beating. The mixture turns from glossy to matte when ready to set."
            },
            {
              "symptom": "Mixture seized into a ball",
              "cause": "Water touched melted chocolate.",
              "fix": "Add a teaspoon of warm cream or water and stir until smooth — this is the trick. Drier seizing needs more liquid; thin seizing wants less."
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Variations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Flavoured version: stir in a teaspoon of vanilla, almond, or peppermint extract once the mixture is off the heat."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Dip-coated: once set, dip pieces in melted dark chocolate and let drip on baking paper."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Make ahead, freezing, leftovers"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Best fresh. Leftovers keep two days in the fridge; reheat covered with a splash of liquid."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
